Booking.com Test

This past June Booking.com performed a test on their image thumbnails. The traditional version suggested different places in a tile-style layout. The test version suggested places as well as specific lodging options below. They made this change on several items and measured booking amount for the change over a week time period.

Airbnb Test

Months ago Airbnb ran this A/B test on their listing pages where they showed price totals for a given date range. This was one step beyond the already visible day rates (in the control). They also used default dates for the total calculation when someone didnt enter a date, or user specified dates when users expressed them. They measured the booking rate per version

Preliminaries

First the Analysts at Airbnb completed a preliminary sample size study. They were interested in finding a difference in purchase rates of 10%. Their current purchase rate is 3.45%

Bol Test

Bol is a a leading online retailer in the Netherlands. They tested a smaller button with less padding against a slightly more bloated one. They measured the number of times the buttons were clicked.

Analysis

iter=100000
a=32+1
b=1224+1
a1=27+1
b1=1359+1
count<-c()
for (i in 1:iter){
A<-rbeta(1, a, b)
B<-rbeta(1, a1, b1)
count[i]<-ifelse(A>B, 1, 0)


}
pdiff<-sum(count)/iter
pdiff
## [1] 0.84804

Parachute Effectiveness Study

The United States Air Force performed a parachute effectiveness for the population of fall semester ISA/STA students at Miami University. The study consisted of 20 randomly selected students who were randomly assigned to have a parachute or not. Those who were assigned to have no parachute put on a fake parachute pack. The 20 personnel were flown to a height of 3000ft and instructed to jump out of the plane in a specified order. The ground crew measured survival of the personnel. Of course the study was double blind (meaning the personnel nor the crew who was given the fake parachute packs). Below is the code for the two levels of randomization.
